    <h1>Morning Reset — A Simple Routine to Make Every Day Count</h1>

    <p>
      Mornings don’t need to be perfect.  
      They don’t need to be productive from the first minute.  
      They simply need to *begin with intention*.
    </p>

    <p>
      A **Morning Reset** is a gentle 5–10 minute ritual that clears your mind, resets your energy, and prepares you emotionally for the day — without pressure, without strict rules, and without the unrealistic routines you see online.
    </p>

    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>1. Why a Morning Reset Works</h2>
    <p>
      Many people wake up overwhelmed — notifications, messages, responsibilities, unfinished tasks.
      A morning reset slows down the chaos and gives your brain a moment to breathe before it jumps into the day.
    </p>

    <p>This ritual works because it:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>reduces morning stress</li>
      <li>creates emotional clarity</li>
      <li>gives a gentle structure to your day</li>
      <li>activates motivation naturally (not through pressure)</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="buy-box">
      ✨ Best planner for morning rituals:  
      <br><strong>Rise & Shine 2026 — Fresh Start Planner</strong>  
      <br><a href="https://amzn.to/4i6Ciie" target="_blank">Buy on Amazon</a>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 2 -->
    <h2>2. The 5-Minute “Core Reset”</h2>
    <p>Here is the simplest version — perfect for busy minds and busy mornings:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>1. Light + Water (30 sec)</strong> — open the curtains and drink a small glass of water.</li>
      <li><strong>2. One Intention (1 min)</strong> — write ONE sentence: “Today I need…”</li>
      <li><strong>3. Three Tasks (1–2 min)</strong> — choose only 3 tasks for the day.</li>
      <li><strong>4. Slow Breath (1 min)</strong> — inhale 4 seconds, exhale 6 seconds.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      This takes less than 5 minutes, but completely changes the emotional tone of your day.
    </p>

    <!-- SECTION 3 -->
    <h2>3. A Soft Morning, Not a Strict One</h2>
    <p>
      Some people feel guilty because they cannot follow complex routines like “5 a.m. miracle mornings”.
      That’s fine — those routines are not made for every mind.
    </p>

    <p>Your version may look like:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>waking up slowly</li>
      <li>stretching for 20 seconds</li>
      <li>sitting quietly for 1 minute</li>
      <li>writing one tiny goal</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Soft mornings build **consistency**.  
      Strict mornings build **burnout**.
    </p>

    <!-- SECTION 4 -->
    <h2>4. Align Your Planner With Your Morning Reset</h2>
    <p>
      Your planner should support your routine — not complicate it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Choose planners with:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>clean pages</li>
      <li>space for short lists</li>
      <li>morning intention or gratitude prompts</li>
      <li>a calm aesthetic</li>
    </ul>

